    <!-- ==================== SHIFTS & AUTO-LOGOUT ==================== -->
    <div class="help-topic" id="topic-shifts">
      <h2><i class="bi bi-clock-history"></i> Shifts & Auto-Logout</h2>
      <p class="topic-desc">TaskFlow enforces shift-based working hours with automatic session management, idle detection, and logout tracking.</p>
      <span class="help-role-badge all">ALL LOCAL USERS</span>

      <h3>How Shifts Work</h3>
      <p>Each user has a configured <strong>shift start time</strong> (e.g., 10:00 AM) and <strong>shift duration</strong> (e.g., 8.5 hours). The system uses these settings to manage your session, send reminders, and trigger auto-logout.</p>

      <h3>Night Shifts (Cross-Midnight)</h3>
      <p>TaskFlow fully supports night shifts that cross midnight (e.g., 19:30 &ndash; 04:30). Key behaviors:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Work date</strong> &mdash; Your tasks and completions are tracked against the date your shift <em>started</em>, not the calendar date. For example, a 19:30 shift starting on April 2 is treated as "April 2" work even after midnight.</li>
        <li><strong>System reminders</strong> &mdash; The task reminder bot uses your shift's work date, so you won't get false "incomplete tasks" messages for the next calendar day while you're still on shift.</li>
        <li><strong>Auto-logout</strong> &mdash; If a user doesn't respond to the shift-end warning, they are logged out at shift end. If they click "Continue", they are auto-logged out 2 hours later. A server-side safety net also closes any stale sessions.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Shift End Warning</h3>
      <p>5 minutes before your shift ends, a modal appears with a countdown timer. You have two options:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Logout Now</strong> &mdash; End your session immediately</li>
        <li><strong>Continue (2 hrs)</strong> &mdash; Extend your session by 2 hours of overtime</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If you do not respond, you are automatically logged out when the countdown reaches zero.</p>

      <h3>Idle Timeout</h3>
      <p>If you are inactive (no mouse movement, clicks, or keyboard input) for 55 minutes, an idle warning modal appears. Click <strong>"I'm Here"</strong> to stay active, or you will be automatically logged out after 5 more minutes of inactivity.</p>

      <h3>Logout Reason During Shift</h3>
      <p>If you choose to log out before your shift ends, a modal appears asking you to provide a reason for the early logout. This helps track why users leave before their shift is complete.</p>
      <div class="help-step">
        <div class="help-step-num">1</div>
        <div class="help-step-content">
          <strong>Click the logout button</strong>
          <p>Click the logout icon in the sidebar during your shift hours.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="help-step">
        <div class="help-step-num">2</div>
        <div class="help-step-content">
          <strong>Select a reason</strong>
          <p>A modal appears with a list of common reasons (e.g., "Personal work", "Feeling unwell", "Network issue", "Power outage", etc.). Select the one that applies.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="help-step">
        <div class="help-step-num">3</div>
        <div class="help-step-content">
          <strong>Confirm logout</strong>
          <p>Click confirm to log out. Your selected reason is recorded alongside the logout event in the attendance log.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Late Login Reason</h3>
      <p>If you log in after your scheduled shift start time, a prompt automatically appears asking you to explain the late login.</p>
      <div class="help-step">
        <div class="help-step-num">1</div>
        <div class="help-step-content">
          <strong>Log in to TaskFlow after your shift start time</strong>
          <p>The system automatically detects that you are late and shows a modal.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="help-step">
        <div class="help-step-num">2</div>
        <div class="help-step-content">
          <strong>Select a reason from the list</strong>
          <p>Common reasons include "Traffic", "Personal errand", "Medical appointment", "Overslept", etc. Select the most appropriate one.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="help-step">
        <div class="help-step-num">3</div>
        <div class="help-step-content">
          <strong>Submit</strong>
          <p>Your late login reason is saved and visible to admins and managers in the attendance dashboard.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Pending Tasks Reminder</h3>
      <p>1 hour before your shift ends, if you have incomplete tasks for the day, a reminder modal pops up listing all pending tasks with direct links to each one.</p>

      <div class="help-tip">
        <i class="bi bi-lightbulb"></i>
        <div>Admins are exempt from shift-based auto-logout and idle timeouts. However, their login/logout times are still tracked for attendance purposes.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ==================== LEAVE MANAGEMENT ==================== -->
    <div class="help-topic" id="topic-leaves">
      <h2><i class="bi bi-calendar-x"></i> Leave Management</h2>
      <p class="topic-desc">Apply for leave, view your leave status, and (for admins/managers) approve or reject leave requests from team members.</p>

      <h3>Applying for Leave</h3>
      <span class="help-role-badge all">ALL USERS</span>
      <div class="help-step">
        <div class="help-step-num">1</div>
        <div class="help-step-content">
          <strong>Go to "Leaves" in the sidebar</strong>
          <p>This opens the leave management page showing your leave history and status.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="help-step">
        <div class="help-step-num">2</div>
        <div class="help-step-content">
          <strong>Click "Apply for Leave"</strong>
          <p>A form appears where you can enter your leave details.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="help-step">
        <div class="help-step-num">3</div>
        <div class="help-step-content">
          <strong>Select the date range</strong>
          <p>Choose the start date (from) and end date (to) for your leave period. For a single day, set both to the same date.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="help-step">
        <div class="help-step-num">4</div>
        <div class="help-step-content">
          <strong>Provide a reason and submit</strong>
          <p>Enter the reason for your leave and click Submit. Your request will be in <strong>Pending</strong> status until an admin or manager acts on it.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Viewing Leave Status</h3>
      <p>On the Leaves page, you can see all your leave requests and their current status:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Pending</strong> &mdash; Awaiting approval</li>
        <li><strong>Approved</strong> &mdash; Leave has been granted</li>
        <li><strong>Rejected</strong> &mdash; Leave request was denied (check remarks for the reason)</li>
      </ul>

      <% if (isAdmin || isManager) { %>
      <h3>Approving / Rejecting Leave</h3>
      <span class="help-role-badge admin">ADMIN</span> <span class="help-role-badge manager">MANAGER</span>
      <p>Pending leave requests from team members appear in the leave list. Click <strong>Approve</strong> or <strong>Reject</strong> and optionally add a remark explaining your decision. The user is notified in real-time.</p>

      <h3>Granting Leave Directly</h3>
      <span class="help-role-badge admin">ADMIN</span> <span class="help-role-badge manager">MANAGER</span>
      <p>You can grant leave directly to a user without requiring them to apply. This creates a pre-approved leave entry. Use this for situations where you know someone will be absent and want to record it proactively.</p>
      <div class="help-step">
        <div class="help-step-num">1</div>
        <div class="help-step-content">
          <strong>Click "Grant Leave"</strong>
          <p>On the Leaves page, click the Grant Leave button.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="help-step">
        <div class="help-step-num">2</div>
        <div class="help-step-content">
          <strong>Select the user and date range</strong>
          <p>Choose which user and the dates for the leave.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="help-step">
        <div class="help-step-num">3</div>
        <div class="help-step-content">
          <strong>Confirm</strong>
          <p>The leave is created as already approved. The user is notified.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <% } %>

      <div class="help-warn">
        <i class="bi bi-exclamation-triangle"></i>
        <div>You cannot apply for leave on past dates or create overlapping leave requests. The system will reject duplicate date ranges.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="help-tip">
        <i class="bi bi-lightbulb"></i>
        <div>When a user is on approved leave, the fallback assignee system automatically redirects their recurring tasks to the designated secondary or tertiary assignee.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ==================== MY PROGRESS ==================== -->
    <div class="help-topic" id="topic-progress">
      <h2><i class="bi bi-graph-up"></i> My Progress</h2>
      <p class="topic-desc">Track your personal performance, task completion history, streaks, and monthly breakdown.</p>
      <span class="help-role-badge all">ALL USERS</span>

